1. Introduction

The CIFAR-100 dataset contains 60,000 color images of 32 x 32 pixels in 3 channels divided into 100 classes. Each class contains 600 images. The training set contains 50,000 images, while the test sets provides 10,000 images. This image taken from the CIFAR repository ( https://www.cs.toronto.edu/~kriz/cifar.html ). This is a classification problem with 100 classes(muti-label classification). We can take a view on this image for more comprehension of the dataset.

3. Define Callbacks

Training will automatically terminate after reaching the required accuraccy

1 cell hidden
class myCallback(tf.keras.callbacks.Callback):
    def on_epoch_end(self, epoch, logs={}):
        if(logs.get('accuracy')>0.90):
            print("\nReached 90% accuracy so cancelling training!")
            self.model.stop_training = True
            
callbacks=myCallback()

4.1 Simple Convolutional Neural Networks or CNN

In the first stage, Our net will learn 32 convolutional filters, each of which with a 3 x 3 size. The output dimension is the same one of the input shape, so it will be 32 x 32 and activation is relu, which is a simple way of introducing non-linearity, folowed by another 32 convolutional filters, each of which with a 3 x 3 size and activation is also relu. After that we have a max-pooling operation with pool size 2 x 2. In the next stage in the deep pipeline, Our net will learn 64 convolutional filters, each of which with a 3 x 3 size. The output dimension is the same one of the input shape and activation is relu; folowed by another 64 convolutional filters, each of which with a 3 x 3 size and activation is also relu. After that we have a max-pooling operation with pool size 2 x 2, followed by 2 convolutional layer with 128 filters each and one max-pooling layer with pooling size 2x2.

And the Final stage in the deep pipeline is a flatten layer which convert 3D input to 1D vector which act as input layer to Fully Connected layer, and a dense network with 512 units and relu activation followed by another dense network with 256 layers and a output layer with softmax activation with 100 classes as output, one for each category.

9 cells hidden

Build Model

1 cell hidden
model=tf.keras.models.Sequential([
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', padding='same', input_shape=(32,32,3)),
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(2,2),
                            
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, (3,3), padding='same', activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(2,2),
                            
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(128, (3,3), padding='same' , activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(128, (3,3), activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(2,2),
                            
                            tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
                            
                            tf.keras.layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.Dense(100, activation='softmax')
])
model.summary()

4.2 CNN with Dropouts

A dropouts layer is added in the previous model, it removes the nodes randomly which helps in prevent overfitting

Build Model

8 cells hidden
model=tf.keras.models.Sequential([
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', padding='same', input_shape=(32,32,3)),
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(2,2),
                            tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.1),
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, (3,3), padding='same', activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(2,2),
                            tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2),
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(128, (3,3), padding='same' , activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(128, (3,3), activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(2,2),
                            tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.4),
                            tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
                        
                            tf.keras.layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2),
                            tf.keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.1),
                            tf.keras.layers.Dense(100, activation='softmax')
])

4.3 CNN with Dropouts and Batch Normalization

A batch Normalization layer is added in previous model, it is used to make artificial neural networks faster and more stable through normalization of the input layer by re-centering and re-scaling.

9 cells hidden

Build Model

1 cell hidden
model=tf.keras.models.Sequential([
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', padding='same', input_shape=(32,32,3)),
                            tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(axis=-1),
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', padding='same'),
                            tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(axis=-1),
                            tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(2,2),
                            tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.1),
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, (3,3), padding='same', activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(axis=-1),
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu', padding='same'),
                            tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(axis=-1),
                            tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(2,2),
                            tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2),
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(128, (3,3), padding='same' , activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(axis=-1),
                            tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(128, (3,3), activation='relu', padding='same'),
                            tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(axis=-1),
                            tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(2,2),
                            tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.4),
 
                            tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
                        
                            tf.keras.layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
                            tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2),
                            tf.keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'),
                            tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
                            tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.1),
                            tf.keras.layers.Dense(100, activation='softmax')
])

5. Results

  1. Simple Convolutional Neural Networks perfom well on training set with more than 90% accuracy but got stuck in validation set at 30%, reason being, our model tend to overfit which lag our test and validation accuracy.
  2. CNN with Dropouts managed to reduce overfitting and increase the validation accuraccy upto 50% which is very close to training accuracy i.e. around 60%.
  3. CNN with Dropouts and Batch Normalization increased both training accuracy and validation accuracy upto great extent, training accuracy is jumped to 90% and validation accuracy jumped to 60%, there is a possiblity that our model was converging quite faster than required rate which results in massive difference in training accuracy and validation accuracy.
  4. CNN with Dropouts, Batch Normalization and Augmentation slows our training maybe due to increase in data but it also imporves our model accuraccy upto greatest extent, with negligible difference in training and validation accuracy i.e. best performance with 53% accuracy each after 100 epochs.
  5. CNN with Transfer Learning used pretrained weights and more number of parameters than above model, it gave accuracy of 37% on training set and 32% on validation set after 100 epochs.

The last two models were not terminated by callbacks, so they could have yeild more accuraccy if trained for 500 epochs or more.
